Several answers here uses [`Integer.toHexString(int)`](http://java.sun.com/javase/6/docs/api/java/lang/Integer.html#toHexString%28int%29); this is doable, but with some caveats. Since the parameter is an `int`, a widening primitive conversion is performed to the `byte` argument, which involves sign extension.

```java
byte b = -1;
System.out.println(Integer.toHexString(b));
// prints &quot;ffffffff&quot;
```

The 8-bit `byte`, which is signed in Java, is sign-extended to a 32-bit `int`. To effectively undo this sign extension, one can mask the `byte` with `0xFF`.

```java
byte b = -1;
System.out.println(Integer.toHexString(b &amp; 0xFF));
// prints &quot;ff&quot;
```

Another issue with using `toHexString` is that it doesn&#39;t pad with zeroes:

```java
byte b = 10;
System.out.println(Integer.toHexString(b &amp; 0xFF));
// prints &quot;a&quot;
```

Both factors combined should make the `String.format` solution more preferable.

